        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Based on the SMA spectral image of the 212-GHz pyrimidine bandhead (Fig. 3(a)), we estimate the largest source scale to be around 12”. On the other hand, we estimate the typical source size of pyrimidine to be around 2”, as disclosed by the SMA image of the 342- GHz bandhead emission (Fig. 3(a)) and the ALMA pyrimidine image at 212-GHz (Fig 5(a)).

To unambiguously identify a complex organic molecule, we need to detect as many molecular transitions as possible to avoid misidentification of chance interlopers. Therefore, if only going after a few (blended) bandheads at higher frequencies for detections, we may not be able to make an unambiguous detection. As demonstrated in the ALMA 212-GHz spectrum (Fig. 5(b)), although we did detect two non-band pyrimidine lines outside the 212-GHz bandhead, we encountered a problem in resolving the individual transitions within the 212-GHz bandhead into discernible (multi-)lines as a result of low spectral resolution applied. The spectral resolution adopted for our 212-GHz Cycle-0 data is 876 kHz (or a channel spacing of 488 kHz and 0.69 km/s in velocity space). In Orion KL, the typical linewidth of a weak molecular line is around 2.0 to 2.5 km/s. Thus, to ensure detections of pyrimidine bandheads and individual bandhead lines within, a spectral resolution of 488 kHz is adopted for all three Science Goals. However, at 212 GHz, because it is very close to the edge of Band 6, we have little freedom in putting the USB and LSB bandheads at the center of spectral windows. As a consequence, some of the targeted (non-)bandhead lines will not be covered if we stick to the 937.5-MHz bandwidth only. To include most of the target lines in Band 6 at 212/230 GHz, we will have to also apply the 1875-MHz bandwidth, even at a lower spectral resolution. In such case, we have little choice but is forced to exceed the 12 MB/s soft limit inevitably.

The expected line intensities of pyrimidine doublets vary between 30 and 60 mJy/bm at 212 GHz (Fig 5(b)). Please note the continuum subtraction was not properly executed. To leave more safety margin, an expected line intensity of 40 mJy/bm was adopted. An S/N ratio of 8 is obtained for an rms of 5 mJy/bm at 212 GHz in Band 6. At 342 and 348 GHz in Band 7, the pyrimidine lines are expected to be a factor of 3 weaker, i.e., ~15 mJy/bm, than that at 212 GHz assuming an excitation temperature of 100 K (here we did not consider corrections for possible beam dilution as source sizes vary largely; Figs 3 &amp; 5). An rms of 5 mJy/bm in Band 7 was thus adopted for an S/N ratio of 3.  However, pyrimidine bandheads are more compact toward higher frequency, the S/N ratio is thus expected to be higher than 3 and close to 5 in practice.

Besides the three proposed bandheads at 212, 342 and 348 GHz, because the adjacent pyrimidine bandheads are separated by ~6 GHz, we are fortunate enough to include three more bandheads at 231, 329, and 360 GHz into the opposite sidebands. In total, we have included three pairs of pyrimidine bandheads in our corf setups:
1) Band 6: 212 GHz (J  34) and 231 GHz (J  37);
2) Band 7, 329 GHz (J  53) and 342 GHz (J  55);
3) Band 7, 348 GHz (J  56) and 360 GHz (J  58).
</prj:justificationText>
