    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Many complex organic molecules found in interstellar clouds are prebiotically important and have essential functions in terrestrial biochemistry. Pyrimidine, the building block of nucleic acid, is a key molecule for astrobiology, and was detected in meteorites and may be components of Halley's CHON dust. Although the formation of prebiotic molecules in extraterrestrial environment and their contribution to the origin of life remains unsettled, the connection between interstellar organic chemistry, meteoritic pyrimidines, and the emergence of life on early Earth would be strengthened with the discovery of pyrimidine.  Our prior search using the JCMT and SMA in Orion KL suggests possible detections of pyrimidine bandheads at 212 and 342 GHz. A serendipitous search in Cycle 0 data discloses likely pyrimidine doublet-lines near the 212-GHz bandhead, though higher spectral resolution is needed for an unequivocal firm detection. The proposed observations will not only test the idea that grain-surface reactions lead to organic ring isomers, more importantly, a detection of pyrimidine will have fundamental implications for astrobiology, thus of the great interest of the general public.</prp:abstract>
